english:
  title: Epitaph for Lord Yu of Seoryeong, Posthumously Named Munhui, Minister of Loyalty, Diligence, Integrity and Righteousness, Greatly Transformed the Realm
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Among the ministers of Hyeonreung there was one named Lord Munhui of the Yu clan, whose personal name was Suk and courtesy name was Sunbu. In the year Sinsaji of the Zhizheng era, he departed for the Yuan capital as an attendant scholar, following Hyeonreung for eleven years until he received the new calendar and returned eastward to our realm. For fifteen years he participated in and oversaw matters of state secrets. Upon his retirement to his native place, he avoided the disaster of Chwisung for four years. Four years after his death, Chwisung met its reckoning, and six years thereafter he received the honor of being enshrined in the Great Chamber. Three years later, Lee Saek of Hansan inscribed this epitaph at the request of his son, the Minister of Secret Council.

    Alas, how could I but take up the brush? In the year Byeongsu of Zhizheng, when my late father Gajeong promulgated the new calendar in the east, Lord Munhui came with him, and thus I first gained his direct acquaintance. Later, serving Hyeonreung together, whenever I spoke rashly and incurred displeasure, the Lord would invariably rescue me. In inscribing his tomb, I could not refuse this duty on grounds of propriety.

    According to the biographical account compiled by his son-in-law Yi Haeng, the Yu clan originated from Seozhou. His grandfather, Commissioner Yu, served as Suseung Langwi and Hamun Chihou. His father Hong, enfeoffed as Chamui Pyeongri and Superior Guard, and his paternal grandfather Seonggye, who held rank as Tongui Daebu, Great Keeper of Rites, and Overseer of the Tea Service—these three generations formed his lineage. His mother of the Kang clan, enfeoffed as Dochekui Chanseongsaja, was surnamed Munse and was his maternal grandfather. He had two wives: of the Yang clan and of the Wu clan.

    His son Shil served as Bongyik Daebu, Vice Minister of Secret Council, Counselor of the State Council and Commander of the Imperial Secretariat. His son Hu held rank as Bongsang Daebu and Grand Recorder of Military Affairs. He had three daughters. The eldest married Kim Jachung, magistrate of the Bureau of Public Works; the second married Choe Jeongryeo, Vice Commandant of the Board of Rites—both born of the Yang clan. The youngest married Yi Haeng, Vice Commissioner of the Warehouse of Righteousness—born of the Wu clan.

    Among his grandsons, from the Vice Minister came Hyegang, appointed Commander; Hyenam, who devoted himself to Buddhist learning; and Hyehwa, appointed to a scattered post. A granddaughter married Seong Seog-in, who achieved first place in the examination of the year Jeongsa and served as Suseung Langwi and Keeper of Ritual Records. The Grand Recorder had sons named Gi and Han, and a daughter. His other grandchildren include sons Bun and Dam from the magistrate, and Jeok and Jeok from the Vice Commissioner, with another daughter, and a single daughter from the commandant.

    When the Lord first entered the academy, the headmaster dreamed that he saw the courtyards swept clean. Asked what this meant, the master replied, "Commissioner Yu of the Chancellery comes." The next day the Lord arrived, and the master marveled at this omen. At sixteen, in the year Sinmi, he passed the examination for the literati degree, with Councillor Kim Uyou as chief examiner. At twenty-five, in the year Gyeonggin, he passed the examination for the advanced degree, with Minister Kim Young-don and Minister of State An Chuk as his patrons.

    In Sinsaji of Zhizheng, the Lord received appointment as magistrate of Andong. It happened that Hyeonreung, as elder brother of the king and Prince of Gangneung, went to attend the Yuan court, and the Lord, abandoning his post, followed him. Four years later, in Gabin, when Myeongryeung ascended the throne, many of Gangneung's attendants abandoned their principles, yet the Lord alone remained steadfast. Myeongryeung honored his integrity and appointed him to Gilchang Prefecture and later promoted him to officer in Gaesong. The Lord grew ever firmer in his resolve.

    Once, visiting his mother in the realm, the historians and literary officials jointly recommended him for appointment as compiler of the Spring and Autumn Annals. The Lord said, "The scholar-official ranks are carefully chosen. Though I lack talent, I may yet bring comfort to my mother." Thus he accepted. This was the year of calendar distribution. The following year, when the records of the Loyal and Righteous were completed, he was commanded to ride the imperial relay and deposit them in the Sea Seal Archives. In autumn he was promoted to officer of the Three Offices, then promptly resigned and returned to the capital.

    At this time, officials of the appointment board deemed it fitting to register and employ him as historian, given his merit. He was appointed to rank six. When Myeongryeung passed away, Minister Wang led in drafting a petition requesting that Hyeonreung succeed to the throne, with support from the elder officials and various ministers presented to the Central Secretariat. Gajeong himself held the brush. As command was about to be issued, the Lord heard that his mother lay ill and requested immediate leave. When some dissuaded him, he replied, "Loyalty and filial piety differ in name but not in substance—they maintain only a proper order. Should filial duty be abandoned, whence shall loyalty spring? Moreover, the days for loyalty are many, but the days for filial duty are few. Should the worst occur, what good shall regret bring?" He departed at once, and his mother, seeing him, rejoiced so greatly that her illness vanished.

    Later, following my father Gajeong to Mount Geumgang and gazing upon the Eastern Sea, the Lord said, "The royal residence at the capital now stands as before. I cannot linger here long." Thus he returned to the capital in Gichwuk, the first year of Chongryeung. In Sinmyo, the ninth month, when Hyeonreung ascended the throne, the Lord received appointment upon his return at Liaoyang Province as Vice Minister of the Secret Council. He was raised to rank of Bonggang Daebu and given responsibilities in the Bureau of Edicts, the Chancellery, and the Historical Records—all while participating in and resolving matters of state. Yet without royal summons, he never once entered the inner chambers.

    The next year he was promoted to Right Vice Minister of Secret Council, but as Prime Minister Cho Ilsin harbored ill will toward him, he petitioned for leave and retired to his estate at Deoksu. When he later suffered the loss of his father, Cho Ilsin gathered discontents and had those he disliked put to death, though he soon met his own ruin. In the fourth month of Gyesa, the Lord was recalled to service as Vice Minister. In the second month of Gapo, he transferred to Left Vice Minister overseeing Military Affairs. In the first month of Eulmi, he presided over the examination for the National Academy, selecting ninety-nine candidates including Jeon Ik. He received appointment as Bongyik Daebu, Judge of the Bureau of Rites, Chief Editor of the Bureau of Edicts, Associate Director of the Historical Records, and Senior Guard.

    That autumn he was twice promoted—to Minister of Public Works and Minister of State Affairs. In Byeongsin, when Minister Kang descended the mountain bearing incense for Geumgang, the Lord was commanded to accompany him. Upon arriving, the minister said, "My illness has worsened. I wish to remain here. See that this is properly explained." Thus the Lord stayed at Cheongryeon Temple for several months. When the king summoned him, he reluctantly returned to court.

    In the fifth month, when the Ki clan's rebellion erupted, the Lord entered the Secret Council as Chief Editor. When the new system of offices was implemented, he became Silver-ranked Grand Commandant, Direct Scholar of the Privy Council, Retainer of the Literary Academy, and Supreme General. When order was restored, he received the iron credential of Minister of Stability. He remarked to his colleagues, "A minister's tablet is also a record of crimes. Let us encourage one another to preserve our integrity to the end, as did the house of Guozi of Fenyang." He also said, "The gentleman does not form factions. I shall never ally with any faction. Let us together serve the throne with undivided hearts—thus shall we prosper."

    Soon he was transferred to Vice Minister. In Jeongyu, he was promoted to Associate Director of the State Council. In Gihae, he advanced to Director of the Observatory. In the winter of Sinchuk, when bandit forces invaded Hwangju with devastating force, the court was bewildered. The Lord, speaking with calm deliberation, proposed the strategy of the southern journey. He said, "The realm depends upon walls and granaries. Now our walls are incomplete and our storehouses empty. Should the bandits surround us, how shall we defend?" Upon reaching Andong, he became Minister of the Privy Council and Chief Retainer of the Literary Academy, charged with co-editing the National History.

    When the bandits were defeated the next year, the three generals' accomplishments grew ever greater, and they grew envious. They murdered General Cheng Seyun and declared, "Bandit-worthy though we became, Yu remained within the inner circle, ever devising stratagems. This one is dangerous—best to remove him." Learning of this, the Lord reported to the king, "When many harbor resentment, it cannot be resisted. The generals oppose me only because I stand at Your Highness's side. Should you drive me forth, I am but a commoner—who would then regard me?" Thus he was sent away as Governor of the Eastern Capital.

    Within ten days of his arrival, his policies had already brought contentment to the people. When the court had established the generals' crimes and called him back in the third month to the rank of Minister of State with the enfeoffment of Kwangjeong Daebu, he received the title "Minister of Loyalty, Diligence, Integrity and Righteousness." Officials and people lamented, "Why not leave him for several months to gather greater fruit?"

    That autumn, when the court moved to Cheongju, he served as Director of Examinations, selecting thirty-three worthy candidates including Park Shil—earning praise for his discernment. In winter he transferred to Minister of State overseeing the Observatory. When Princess Hong, wife of a marquis, fell into destitution in Namyang, the king took pity and sent an edict to Inspector Yi Jitae to provide her with grain. Yi Jitae said, "All royal commands must pass through the Two Ministries before being promulgated. What shall I do?" He dared neither refuse nor open the edict, so it lay upon his desk. The princess, angered, sent it back to the inner palace. The king deemed Yi Jitae disrespectful and ordered his arrest with manacles—a fate uncertain and grave.

    The Lord insisted this could not be done. The king grew furious, saying, "Must all affairs pass through your hands?" and dismissed him. But soon he recalled the Lord, who entered prostrate and fully explained Yi Jitae's words, adding, "Should Your Highness's anger continue, I fear future generations will use this as a pretext." Thereupon the matter was dropped. Later the king summoned him again, and the Lord apologized, "I have long received Your Highness's grace yet rendered no service, only impudently touched the Heavenly Authority with words—my fault admits no pardon." The king bestowed gold upon him, saying, "This is a reward for your upright speech."

    When the Lord occasionally petitioned to retire and preserve his remaining years, the king after long consideration granted him leave, enfeoffing him as Lord of Seoryeong. He requested permission to make offerings at his ancestors' graves. The next day the king called him again. In Gyemyo, when the king returned to the capital and made a temple his temporary palace, bandits at midnight stole within, slaying the night watch. The king fled to a secret chamber, hearing the assassins converse: "Why have you come late?" one asked. The other replied, "We delayed killing Hong and Yu." When generals with troops arrived to rescue the king, the Lord entered with them. The king said, "I thought you dead and would never see you again. Upon seeing your face, I doubted whether events had truly unfolded. Hearing your voice, my doubt dissolved." That very day he entered the city and was appointed to the Royal Secretariat, adding the title Inspector-General in the tenth month.

    In Gapchin, he was promoted to Minister of State, Associate Director of the Council, Chief Editor of the Bureau of Edicts, Director of Historical Records, Senior Guard, and Governor of the Observatory. In the third month of Eulsa, he received the additional enfeoffment of Lord of Seoryeong—a decision made because of Sindon.

    Sindon, coming and going within the palace, outwardly took refuge in Buddhism while harboring deception within. The Lord gradually restrained him. But when Sindon grew his hair and took the cap, becoming Chief of the Grand Council and wielding the power of reward and punishment, he slandered the great ministers—his influence became truly fearsome. Yet the Lord, though repeatedly invited, never once visited him. That autumn, the Lord requested to retire to the countryside, and he built a home on Gaya Mountain in Isан County, living in leisure and solitude. The Hermit of Gyeongsan sent him a poem containing the lines: "Once you calmed the realm in times of danger, / Now you become an immortal on level ground."

    In Musin, Sindon's schemes, long cultivated, finally bore fruit, and he had the Lord strangled in Yeonggwang County on the twenty-first of the twelfth month. During his retirement, whenever the Lord heard that national affairs had grown strange, he would weep. When his calamity came, his family, remembering his former words, sent him incense and urged him to flee, offering a fine horse and saying, "You must choose for yourself." But the Lord replied, "I have considered it. The king and father are as Heaven—can one escape Heaven? Moreover, life and death are Heaven's decree; one should accept them peacefully. If I flee, where would I go?" When death came, his countenance remained peaceful as before, and all who witnessed it wept.

    When Sindon's crimes were exposed and he fell from power, the king at last understood and grieved deeply. A royal edict was issued vindicating the Lord and granting him the posthumous name Munhui. On the eleventh day of the first month of Imja, he was buried with full rites in Daepoong County, Gaya Valley. In the eleventh month of Byeongchin, when Hyeonreung was enshrined in the ancestral temple, the court debated the Lord's enshrinement there as well, and this honor was granted to him.

    Such were the great honors bestowed upon him after death. As for the subtlety of his counsel and the particularity of his conduct—when recommending others for office, he never spoke of it to the person involved; when dismissing or removing officials, he never decided matters on his own authority; when facing great affairs or resolving grave doubts, he never hesitated in his judgment. Truly he possessed both penetrating wisdom and compassionate forbearance. Small wonder that his eldest son proved worthy.

    Thus I inscribe:

    Munhui's nature—
    the purity of fine jade.
    Munhui's conduct—
    the gentleness of warm wind.

    When facing events, precise and strong;
    with compassionate heart,
    he aided our Hyeonreung,
    equal in perilous and peaceful times.

    He bade farewell and withdrew,
    the royal command became his fate.
    What could he do against Destiny?
    Yet time brought vindication,
    and he ascended to the Great Chamber.
    True were his deeds and merit.
    Heaven's way knows no error—
    brilliant as facing the light.

    Upon this stone in the quiet tomb,
    we tell it to those wise in ages to come.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Hyeonreung (玄陵): The posthumous name of King Gongmin of Goryeo, who was exiled in the Yuan court before being restored to power.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhizheng era: The reign period of the Yuan emperor Toγon Temür (1341-1368).'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Chwisung: Likely referring to a factional conflict or purge at court.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Myeongryeung (明陵): The Yuan emperor who succeeded during the political upheavals described.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Gajeong (稼亭): The courtesy name of the author''s father, Lee Jayun, a renowned official.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Ki clan''s rebellion (奇氏之難): An internal conflict at the Goryeo court involving the powerful Ki family faction.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Sindon (辛旽): A Buddhist monk who gained extraordinary political influence and became the true power behind the throne, eventually orchestrating the death of upright officials like Yu Suk.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Iron credential (鐵券): A symbol of merit and immunity from certain punishments, though as Yu Suk notes, it could also become a record of one''s rise and potential fall.'
